.TH FITTSMON-GUI 1 "January 2026" "fittsmon-gui 0.0.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
fittsmon-gui \- Simple graphical configuration tool for `fittsmon`.

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B fittsmon-gui

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B fittsmon-gui
is a simple graphical user interface (GUI) for configuring screen corner hotspots. It provides an easy way for non-technical users to map mouse events (clicks, wheel scrolling, mouse enter/leave) in screen corners to shell commands.
The GUI automatically detects all connected monitors and allows per-monitor, per-zone, and per-event command configuration.

.SH REQUIREMENTS
.B fittsmon-gui
requires:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Python 3.6 or higher
.IP \(bu 2
PyGObject (GTK 3 bindings)
.IP \(bu 2
fittsmon installed
.IP \(bu 2
xrandr (for monitor detection)
.RE

.SH CONFIGURATION
All configuration is stored in:
.RS
.B ~/.config/fittsmon/fittsmonrc
.RE

.SH USAGE

Start the GUI:
.RS
.B fittsmon-gui
.RE

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Select a monitor from the dropdown.
.IP \(bu 2
Select a zone (corner/edge).
.IP \(bu 2
Select an event to configure.
.IP \(bu 2
Type a shell command in the text field (auto-saves).
.IP \(bu 2
Click "Test" to execute the command immediately.
.IP \(bu 2
Click "Save" to write changes to disk.
.IP \(bu 2
Click "Restart" to reload the 'fittsmon' daemon.
.RE

.SH BUTTONS

.TP
.B Test
Execute the current command immediately to verify it works

.TP
.B Edit File
Open the configuration file in your default text editor (geany, gedit, etc.)

.TP
.B Save
Write all changes to the configuration file

.TP
.B Restart
Kill and restart the 'fittsmon' daemon to activate changes

.SH CONFLICT RESOLUTION

The GUI prevents conflicting wheel event configurations:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Only ONE of WheelUp/WheelUpOnce can be set per zone
.IP \(bu 2
Only ONE of WheelDown/WheelDownOnce can be set per zone
.IP \(bu 2
Enter and Leave can be used together (they are opposite events)
.IP \(bu 2
Button events can coexist with any other events
.RE

When a conflict is detected, the GUI shows a warning and provides a "Clear Conflict" button.

